ry world. Locating profound ambivalence in people's ethical evaluations of gender and fertility control, Paxson offers a far-reaching analysis of conflicting assumptions about what it takes to be a good mother and a good woman in modern Greece, where assertions of cultural tradition unfold against a backdrop of European Union integration, economic struggle, and national demographic anxiety over a falling birth rate.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aBirth controlzGreecezAthensxPublic opinion. 0aFeminist anthropologyzGreecezAthens. 0aMotherhoodzGreecezAthens. 0aPublic opinionzGreecezAthens. 0aWomenzGreecezAthensxSocial conditions. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Gender Studies.2bisacsh  aabortion.  aanthropological study.  aanthropologists.  aathens.  abirth control.  acontemporary greece.  acultural traditions.  aeconomic struggles.  aethical issues.  aethics.  aeurope.  aeuropean union.  afalling birth rate.  afamily planning.  afemininity.  afertility control.  afertility rates.  agender studies.  agreece.  agreek citizens.  agreek demographics.  amodern motherhood.  amotherhood.  anonfiction.  areproductive politics.  asocial analysts.  asocial cultural.  aurban setting.  awomens issues.  awomens roles.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052023820640uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052093713040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520937130423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520937130/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY